e his history of these cataclysmic events from a comfortable exile in Rome. His history enjoyed enormous popularity among Christians, who saw it as a testimony to the world that gave rise to their faith and a record of the suffering of the Jews due to their rejection of Christ. Jews were hardly aware of the book until the Renaissance. In the nineteenth century, Josephus's history became an important source for recovering Jewish history, yet Jewish enthusiasm for his stories of heroism—such as the doomed defense of Masada—has been tempered by suspicion of a writer who betrayed his own people.Goodman provides a concise biography of one of the greatest war narratives ever written, explaining why Josephus's book continues to hold such fascination today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aJewish historiansvBiography. 0aJewsxHistoryy168 B.C.-135 A.D. 0aJewsxHistoryyRebellion, 66-73xHistoriography. 0aRomansxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAgainst Apion.  aAnanias.  aAncient history.  aAntiquities.  aBible.  aCassius Dio.  aChristendom.  aChristian literature.  aChristian.  aChristianity and Judaism.  aChristianity.  aClassical antiquity.  aClassics.  aCowardice.  aDivine retribution.  aEarly Christianity.  aEarly modern period.  aEastern Europe.  aEnthusiasm.  aEssenes.  aExegesis.  aFirst Jewish–Roman War.  aGalilean.  aGentile.  aGiovanni Pico della Mirandola.  aGreek historiography.  aHalevi.  aHaskalah.  aHebraist.  aHebrew Bible.  aHebrew language.  aHegesippus (chronicler).  aHellenistic period.  aHerod the Great.  aHistoriography.  aImpiety.  aJewish education.  aJewish history.  aJewish identity.  aJewish literature.  aJewish philosophy.  aJewish prayer.  aJewish studies.  aJews.  aJohn of Giscala.  aJoseph J